The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 Mumbai, March 24: The government has agreed to create a buffer stock of 20 lakh tonnes of sugar amid expectations of a bumper production in the current season. The decision was taken at the meeting of the Cabinet Committee on Economic Affairs (Ceca), chaired by Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, tonight. The committee has also decided to lift the ceiling on sugar exports and provide subsidies to sugar mills for export. The buffer stock would be created for a maximum of two years, sources said. No official communication could be obtained on the decisions.

 Indore, March 24: Bajaj Auto has said it may build cars to ward off the threat posed by the Tatas Rs 1 lakh car to the two-wheeler market. The jd Power study says that the Tata car will affect the two-wheeler market. If that happens then we would also manufacture cars for the market, Bajaj Auto chairman Rahul Bajaj said.

 Mumbai, March 24: Indias forex reserves increased by $1.55 billion to $195.957 billion in the week ended March 16 against $194.410 billion in the week ended March 9. The reserves dipped by $224 million in the previous week. The foreign currency assets increased by $1.545 billion to $188.603 in the week ended March 16.

 Calcutta, March 24: Bengal will follow the Maharashtra model for refund of value-added tax (VAT) to export-oriented and SEZ units and to domestic manufacturers against their excess payment on input tax, commercial tax commissioner in the state H.K. Dwivedi said.

 Mumbai, March 24: Reserve Bank governor Y.V. Reddy will present the annual policy statement for 2007-08 on April 24. The governor will meet the chief executives of important scheduled commercial banks at 11 am on that day in the Reserve Banks central office, the RBI said.




